  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Coming to Sweden Without a Job Offer</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">There's no job-seeking visa for non-EU citizens. You cannot enter Sweden to look for work—you need a job offer and approved work permit before arrival. Tourist visa doesn't allow job searching. Find the job first, then apply.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Accepting Below-Minimum Salary</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If your salary is below SEK 27,360/month, your permit will be denied. The union will object, and Migrationsverket will reject the application. Ensure your offer meets the minimum AND matches collective agreement standards for your profession.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Delaying Personnummer Registration</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Register at Skatteverket immediately after arrival. Without personnummer, you can't access full healthcare, open bank accounts easily, or use many services. The longer you wait, the more difficult daily life becomes. Bring all required documents on first visit.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Using Certified Employer Fast-Track</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If your employer is certified by Migrationsverket, processing takes 10-20 days instead of months. Ask your employer if they're certified. If not, suggest they apply—it speeds up hiring significantly and helps attract international talent.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Immediate Healthcare Access</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Full healthcare access requires personnummer registration, which takes weeks. Your employer's insurance covers you initially, but you may face administrative issues. Consider travel medical insurance for the gap period if you have health concerns.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Sweden -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Sweden</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Swedish healthcare is tax-funded and decentralized across 21 regions. Quality is high, but wait times for non-urgent care can be significant. The system prioritizes based on medical need, not ability to pay. Once registered with personnummer, you access the same care as any Swedish citizen.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Swedish Healthcare Works</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Vårdcentral (Health Center)</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Register at a local vårdcentral after getting personnummer. This is your primary care provider. GP visits cost SEK 200-350. You can change vårdcentral freely. Many offer drop-in or same-day appointments for urgent issues.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Specialists</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Referral from GP usually required. Wait times vary—can be weeks to months depending on specialty and urgency. The vårdgaranti promises 90 days max, but this isn't always met. Private insurance provides faster specialist access.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Hospitals</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Emergency rooms (akutmottagning) are free for life-threatening situations. Other ER visits cost ~SEK 400. Inpatient care costs SEK 120/day maximum. Major hospitals in Stockholm (Karolinska), Gothenburg (Sahlgrenska), Malmö (Skåne University Hospital) are excellent.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">1177 Vårdguiden</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Call 1177 for healthcare advice 24/7. Nurses assess your situation and advise whether to visit vårdcentral, ER, or self-care. Website 1177.se has health information in English. Very useful for navigating the system.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Finding English-Speaking Care</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Most Swedish healthcare providers speak English, especially in Stockholm, Gothenburg, and Malmö. Some vårdcentraler specifically cater to expats. Major hospitals have interpretation services. Use 1177.se to find providers and check language availability.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Private healthcare (privat vård):</strong> Private clinics like Capio, Aleris, and Doktor24 offer faster appointments. Some accept public funding (you pay same fees as public), others are fully private. With private insurance, you access these with minimal wait. Many employers now include private healthcare as a benefit.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need private health insurance in Sweden?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No—after personnummer registration, public healthcare covers you. Private insurance is optional and primarily used for faster access to specialists and elective procedures. Many Swedish professionals have private insurance through employers. It's a convenience, not a necessity.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the collective agreement requirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Swedish work permits require that your employment terms match collective agreement (kollektivavtal) standards for your industry. This means appropriate salary, working hours, vacation, and insurance. Unions review offers and can object if terms are substandard. This protects workers from exploitation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until permanent residence?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After 4 years of continuous work in Sweden on work permits, you can apply for permanent residence. You must have held valid permits throughout and met all conditions. Permanent residence provides indefinite stay and isn't tied to employment.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers on a work permit?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          For the first 2 years, your permit is tied to the specific employer. Changing jobs requires a new work permit application. After 2 years, you can change employers within the same occupation without new application. After 4 years, you have permanent residence and full flexibility.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family join me?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Spouse/partner and children under 21 can apply for residence permits. Apply simultaneously with your work permit for faster processing. Spouse receives work authorization. Family members access healthcare after personnummer registration.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the personnummer and why is it important?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The personnummer is Sweden's personal identity number—essential for everything from healthcare to banking to phone contracts. You get it by registering at Skatteverket. Without it, daily life is difficult. Apply immediately upon arrival and bring all required documents.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Sweden offers exceptional work-life balance, comprehensive social benefits, and a thriving tech scene. The work permit system is straightforward for skilled workers meeting salary requirements, though processing times can be long. The collective agreement requirement ensures fair terms—your employer must offer market-rate conditions.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Healthcare is tax-funded and excellent quality, though wait times for non-urgent care can be frustrating. The personnummer is essential for full access—register immediately upon arrival. Private insurance is optional but valuable for faster specialist access, especially as many employers now provide it.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      High taxes mean lower take-home pay than gross salary suggests, but you get comprehensive social security, healthcare, and one of the world's best work environments. For tech workers, the Stockholm ecosystem rivals any in Europe. If work-life balance and social benefits matter to you, Sweden delivers.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
